<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="277" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,510,931]" pageId="6" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,466,834,859]" pageId="6" pageNumber="277">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
The straight, parallel-sided parameres (
<figureCitation box="[935,1006,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1319,1341]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,755,1284]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,738,1297]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 7. Aedeagus of Globulosis spp. (A) G. flavus sp. n. (holotype), (B) G. hemisphericus, reproduced from García, 2001, (C) G. hemisphericus from the upper Berbice, Guyana, (D) G. hemisphericus from Manaus, Brazil, (E) G. hemisphericus from Raleighvallen Nature Reserve, Suriname. Scale bar 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292835/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="277">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
A) and yellow to light brown dorsal coloration (
<figureCitation box="[283,352,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1936,1958]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,555,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,555,1914]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus of Globulosis spp. G. hemisphericus (from Suriname): (A) dorsal, (B) lateral, (C) ventral; G. flavus (paratype): (D) dorsal, (E) lateral, (F) ventral. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/293122/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="277">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
D) serve to distinguish this species from 
<taxonomicName box="[833,1029,870,895]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Globulosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="277" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hemisphericus">
<emphasis box="[833,1029,870,895]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="277">G. hemisphericus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in which the outer margins of the parameres are curved along their entire length, and is darker in coloration.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
